{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491575","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491575"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:53:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:53:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"989"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"989","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/989"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.03,0.16,0.01,0.6]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"989"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99916"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"989","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/989"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"989"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82308"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"601"},{"type":"tags","id":"1184"},{"type":"tags","id":"3320"},{"type":"tags","id":"9022"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3005"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3401"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10718"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10821"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28450"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99916","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/99916"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents with a 12-month history of poor vision in her left eye. She describes no other symptoms and otherwise feels well. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination her visual acuity is 6/6 in the right eye and 6/60 in the left. Two years ago her visual acuity was 6/6 in both eyes. Intraocular pressures are 18mmHg in both eyes. In the light, the right pupil is 3mm diameter and reactive, whilst the left is 4mm diameter and sluggish. There is a relative afferent pupillary defect in the left eye. Fundoscopy shows a right pink optic nerve and a left pale optic nerve with no cupping or haemorrhage.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations would be most appropriate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fluorescein angiography","Lumbar puncture","Visual evoked potential (VEP) testing","C-reactive protein","MRI brain and orbits with gadolinium"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has left optic nerve atrophy. This is evidenced by the reduced left visual acuity, impaired reactivity of the pupil, a relative afferent pupillary defect and a pale left optic disc. Anything that causes damage to the optic nerve can cause optic atrophy. There is a large list of differential diagnoses for this case; most notably extrinsic compression, optic neuritis, trauma and also arteritic and non-arteritis anterior ischaemic optic neuropathy. Compressive lesions such as a meningioma, pituitary tumour (adenoma) and lymphoma need to be excluded with an \u003Cstrong\u003EMRI brain and orbits with gadolinium\u003C/strong\u003E. Additionally, this investigation would provide evidence of inflammatory disease (including multiple sclerosis) and ischaemic changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFluorescein angiography \u003C/strong\u003Eis a diagnostic test used to evaluate the blood flow in the retina and choroid. While it can be helpful in assessing conditions such as diabetic retinopathy, retinal vascular occlusions, and choroidal neovascularisation, it is not typically indicated as an initial investigation for a patient presenting with isolated visual loss and optic disc pallor. The clinical presentation described in the case suggests a pathology primarily involving the optic nerve rather than the retina or choroid. Therefore, fluorescein angiography would not be the most appropriate investigation in this context.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELumbar puncture\u003C/strong\u003E may show evidence of raised opening pressure which is seen in idiopathic intracranial hypertension (IIH) and be sent for testing of oligoclonal bands. However, IIH is usually bilateral\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC-reactive protein\u003C/strong\u003E may suggest an underlying inflammatory or infective diagnosis such as TB or SLE, however if these conditions are suspected, other more specific tests should be ordered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVisual evoked potential (VEP) testing\u003C/strong\u003E measures the electrical activity in the visual pathway, from the retina to the visual cortex, in response to visual stimuli. While VEP testing can be valuable in diagnosing optic nerve disorders, such as optic neuritis or demyelinating diseases like multiple sclerosis, it is typically used as a supplementary test to confirm optic nerve dysfunction rather than as an initial investigation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Evidence of optic nerve damage can be clinically diagnosed with an impairment of: visual acuity, visual fields, colour vision, a relative afferent pupillary defect.","MRI with gadolinium is the investigation of choice for suspected optic neuropathy to exclude compressive, inflammatory, and demyelinating causes."],"references":["Bowling B. Kanski\u2019s Clinical Ophthalmology. 8th ed. W B Saunders; 2015.","Ahmad SS, Kanukollu VM. Optic Atrophy. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023. [cited 2025 Apr 23]. Available from: https://europepmc.org/article/nbk/nbk559130"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82308"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"989"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82308","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/82308"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-23T08:35:56+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-23T08:37:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"989"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99916"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://a